entry.title: Copy CpuProbe from services/device/compute_pressure
entry.content:
Makes a copy of ComputePressure's CpuProbe and supporting files, and

alters it to expose probe results for UMA instead of reporting through

the ComputePressure mojo interface. A copy is used instead of moving

it into a common helper since the needs of the UMA metrics and

ComputePressure may diverge.



* The original CpuProbe takes measurements on a timer, and calls the

same RepeatingCallback whenever a new measurement arrives. This

version takes a measurement whenever RequestSample() is called with

a OnceCallback for the result. PageTimelineMonitor will use this to

synchronize the measurements with other UMA histograms it logs.

* Adds an error value (absl::nullopt) if a measurement fails since the

measurements are being exposed directly to the caller. The original

CpuProbe used the measurements to calculate a ComputePressure state

so it handled errors internally.

* Updates test helpers due to interface changes. The generic

CpuProbeTest now calls RequestSample with callback that saves test

results, instead of overriding OnPressureSampleAvailable to save

the results and expecting CpuProbe's internal timer to call it. The

platform-specific tests that call the internal Update() method

directly now call an UpdateAndWaitForSample() helper since Update()

now requires a callback.

* Adds more unit tests on Linux.

entry.title: Check for stale build directory relative to traffic_annotation proto
entry.content:
When a developer attempts to run the auditor with a build directory

which is outdated relative to the chromium repository (eg. they pulled

main without rebuilding the generated traffic_annotation proto or the

chrome target) this can result is confusing errors.



Since there is not much utility to running the auditor on a stale build

directory, display an informative error instead of running it. The

exception to this when the traffic_annotation.proto is being actively

developed, so add in a flag to skip the stale build check.



Testing:



1) Verify the auditor runs with a new build.

autoninja -C out/Default chrome

vpython3 tools/traffic_annotation/scripts/auditor/auditor.py --build-path out/Default

2) Make a note of the modified times of each file.

stat chrome/browser/privacy/traffic_annotation.proto

stat out/Default/pyproto/chrome/browser/privacy/traffic_annotation_pb2.py

3) Add a newline to the proto, verify the modified time.

echo "" >> chrome/browser/privacy/traffic_annotation.proto

stat chrome/browser/privacy/traffic_annotation.proto

4) Verify auditor fails with correct message.

vpython3 tools/traffic_annotation/scripts/auditor/auditor.py --build-path out/Default

5) Verify auditor runs with --skip-stale-build-check.

vpython3 tools/traffic_annotation/scripts/auditor/auditor.py --build-path out/Default --skip-stale-build-check

6) Rebuild and verify auditor runs without the option.

autoninja -C out/Default chrome

vpython3 tools/traffic_annotation/scripts/auditor/auditor.py --build-path out/Default

entry.title: Add hue slider to descriptor d's menu.
entry.content:
Note that descriptor d's color is expected to be set as a hex string in the backend

(customize_chrome_page_handler.cc).



This CL adds another optional to GetWallpaperSearchResults for hues.



This was chosen over



1. Converting the hue in the backend like we do for appearance [1], receiving in the frontend,

then passing it to the backend. *patchset 7 [2] shows this.

2. Converting the hues in the frontend. This requires creating a FE util to convert hues to

hexes, and AFAIK there are no utils that convert hues to anything in the FE.

3. Passing a hue number for all descriptors. The static colored buttons have varying

entry.title: [Extensions] Fix developer mode context check
entry.content:
APIs can be restricted to profiles in developer mode. This is

implemented by storing a bit in a map with an ID for the associated

profile, indicating if developer mode is active. Then, when determining

availability, we check if the bit is set. We do this, among other

places, when checking ExtensionFunction::HasPermission().



There was a bug here in that the ExtensionFunction's check happened

before `ExtensionFunction::browser_context_` was set. This resulted in

checking the developer mode bit for a null context, which was

(naturally) not set. The end result of this was that any

ExtensionFunction::HasPermission() check would fail for an API marked

as developer mode only, regardless of the developer mode setting. This

wasn't caught by our tests, which only exercised API presence in JS as

an indication of correctness.



(This is all okay, because developer-mode-only APIs are still in

development behind a flag and not turned on for any population.)



Fix this and expand the test to verify that the API call can succeed

when developer mode is enabled.

> WebGPUSwapBufferProvider: Don't create SI with unsupported size.

>

> Currently WebGPUSwapBufferProvider::GetNewTexture() always tries

> to create a new shared image even if the size is larger than Dawn's

> maxTextureDimension2D limit. If the hardware cannot create a shared

> image with this size, Chrome will disconnect the GPU channel.

>

> We should skip the shared image creation if the size is larger than

> Dawn's maxTextureDimension2D limit. Because even if the shared image is

> successfully created, a WGPUTexture won't be able to be created from it

> anyway.

>

> This will fix the WebGPU CTS validation tests using getCurrentTexture

> on "overlimit" canvas when Graphite is enabled. Because with Graphite,

> a shared image larger than Dawn's maxTextureDimension2D limit is not

> allowed.

entry.title: Create RootGeometry lazily in IntersectionGeometry
entry.content:
When we call IntersectionObservation::ComputeIntersection in a loop

for intersection observations of the same intersection observer, we

use the same RootGeometry for all invocations.



Now let the caller create optional and pass it to

ComputeIntersection, and IntersectionGeometry emplace it only when

needed.



This simplifies the code by combining the previous two versions of

IntersectionObservation::ComputeIntersection() and

IntersectionGeometry constructors into one, respectively.



This performance impact will be probably trivial for now. This

prepares for IntersectionOptimization to track minimum scroll delta

per IntersectionObservation, with which ComputeIntersection will

have more no-op invocations and layily creating RootGeometry can

probably reduce the cost when a RootGeometry is not needed for any

IntersectionObservation of an observer.

entry.title: WebGPUSwapBufferProvider: Don't create SI with unsupported size.
entry.content:
Currently WebGPUSwapBufferProvider::GetNewTexture() always tries

to create a new shared image even if the size is larger than Dawn's

maxTextureDimension2D limit. If the hardware cannot create a shared

image with this size, Chrome will disconnect the GPU channel.



We should skip the shared image creation if the size is larger than

Dawn's maxTextureDimension2D limit. Because even if the shared image is

successfully created, a WGPUTexture won't be able to be created from it

anyway.



This will fix the WebGPU CTS validation tests using getCurrentTexture

on "overlimit" canvas when Graphite is enabled. Because with Graphite,

a shared image larger than Dawn's maxTextureDimension2D limit is not

allowed.
